"""You can see the description of the task using the code specified in the title on leetcode.
This program has O(n) complexity by time and O(n) by space.

It's a surprisingly simple problem to program, but surprisingly difficult to figure out the solution principle and why it's solved this way.
I thought about it for a long time and, with some hints, found two approaches that were completely clear to me.

1. Exactly half of the people should end up in A. 
We can simply greedily move half of them there, with the smallest possible difference between price A and price B, to get the optimal answer.

2. We can send everyone to A and pay (total_a) price, and then greedily move half of the people, those who will bring the greatest savings (whose B cost is lower than A's cost).
"""

class Solution:
    def twoCitySchedCost(self, costs: List[List[int]]) -> int:
        costs.sort(key=lambda x: x[0] - x[1])
        size = len(costs)
        result = sum(cost[0] for cost in costs[:size // 2]) + sum(cost[1] for cost in costs[size // 2:])
        return result
